==> Framework:-
--> A framework is a set of pre-return code that's helps to build the application fast.
--> Example - spring, angular,Django.

==> spring :- spring is the light weight framework, open source framework user to developed enterprise application
--> 1st diagram.(modules of the spring framework)

==> Spring core:-
--> It is used to create or manage the components in an application.
--> It provides object life cycle management, dependencies injection,IOC(Inversion of control).

==> Bean:-
--> An object that's is created an managed by spring container.
 @Component
 public class FormDbController
 {

 }

==> IOC:-
--> IOC is a design principle.
--> Inverting the work to an external entity.
--> spring framework implements IOC.

==> Containers:-
--> containers are used to managed the object life cycle.
--> containers create object inject dependencies an managed object life cycle.

==> Types of container
**** Bean factory
**** Application controller
--> It doesn't support E loading web application and AOP.

==> Dependencies injection:-
--> Providing the required references or dependencies to a class from outside instead of creating them inside the class.

--> Types:-

**=> Constructor Injection:-
  @Component
  class FormDbController
  {
   	FormDbService formDbService;
  	FormDbController(FormDbService service)
  	{
  		this.formDbService = service;
  	}
 }

**=> setter or field Injection:-
 @Component
 Class FormDbController
 {
 	@Autowired
 	FormDbService formDbService;
 }

==> scopes:- It is used to informs spring containers the no of objects to be created.
--> Types:-
**> Singleton :- One object per container(default scope).
**> prototype :- Every time new object is created when we call getBean() or every time when we request object from a container.
**> request   :- One object per HTTP request.
**> session   :- One object per HTTP session.

==> @componentScan:- It returns spring container where to scan for the components.
** example:- @ComponentScan( base Package ="com.jsp.usm");

==> @Configuration:- This annotation indicates the class contains bean definition that spring containers should manage.
==> @Component:- It tells the spring container to create and managed the object of a class.
==> @Bean:- These annotation is used to manually defined a spring bean inside configuration class.
--> The object returned by these method should be managed by spring container.

==> NOTE:- @Bean is used on a method which returns object and inside a class which is having @configuration annotation.

 @Configuration
 public class AppConfiguration
 {
    @Bean
 	public Datasource.getDataSource()
 	{
  		return new HikariDataSource();
 	}
 }

==> @ AutoWired:- This annotation is used for dependencies injection.
--> It automatically injects a dependencies (object form the spring container).


==> @Primary:- This annotation is used when multiple objects of same type exists.
--> The object having @primary is treated as the default Bean.
  @Configuration
  public class AppConfiguration
  {
  	@Bean
  	public Datasource.getDataSource()
  	{
   		return new HikariDataSource();
  	}
  	@Primary
 	@Bean
  	public Datasource.getDataSource()
 	{
   	    return new HikariDataSource();
  	}
  }

==> @Qualifier:- It is used to tell spring framework to injects a specific object with the given name .
